subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#accordingTo>
rdfs_comment:
Information about the authorship of this concept which uses the Name in their
         sense (i.e. secundum, sensu). Could be an institution or collection or team of individuals.
         Equivalent to TCS /DataSet/TaxonConcepts/TaxonConcept/AccordingTo/AccordingToDetailed

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#hasName>
rdfs_comment:
The TaxonName for this concept. Equivalent to TCS
         /DataSet/TaxonConcepts/TaxonConcept/Name

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#TaxonConcept>
rdfs_comment:
Representation of a TaxonConcept. Equivalent to TCS
         /DataSet/TaxonConcepts/TaxonConcept

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept>
rdfs_comment: Version 0.3 removed subclass declarations to classes outside of this ontology in accordance with Recommendation 2.9 of the VoMaG Report http://www.gbif.org/resource/80862
dc_description:
Ontology describing the metadata returned for LSIDs that are used for Taxon
         Concepts.

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept>
rdfs_comment:
This is not a full rendering of TaxonConcept as
         presented in the Taxon Concept Schema 1.0. Not all the possible concept-concept
         relationships have been modelled just the basic set theory and taxonomic hierarchy
         relationships. RelationshipAssertions have not been included. These omissions will be
         addressed in collaboration with the first data provider/consumer pairs who need to make use
         them. FIXME: Wonder Web OWL
            Ontology Validator
dc_description:
Ontology describing the metadata returned for LSIDs that are used for Taxon
         Concepts.

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#accordingToString>
rdfs_comment:
A string representation of the according to for this concept. Equivalent to TCS
         /DataSet/TaxonConcepts/TaxonConcept/AccordingTo/Simple

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#circumscribedBy>
rdfs_comment:
A specimen that forms part of the circumscription of this taxon. Equivalent to
         TCS /DataSet/TaxonConcepts/TaxonConcept/SpecimenCircumscription

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#describedBy>
rdfs_comment:
A description that delimits this taxon. Equivalent to TCS
         /DataSet/TaxonConcepts/TaxonConcept/CharacterCircumscription

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#DoesNotInclude>
base_definition: Set Relationship: Concept 2 is not a subset of Concept 1

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#DoesNotOverlap>
base_definition:
Set Relationship: Concepts 1 and 2 have no members/children in
         common

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#Excludes>
base_definition:
Set Relationship: Concept 1 does not overlap or include Concept
         2

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#fromTaxon>
rdfs_comment: The host taxon in this relationship.

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#hasInformation>
rdfs_comment: A piece of information about this TaxonConcept.

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#HasSynonym>
base_definition:
The target concept is considered a synonym of the current concept. This is
         an ambiguous relationship. It can mean: 1) a nomenclatural relationship where all that is
         implied is that the type of the target concept is included in the current circumscription.
         This is more precisely expressed as a specimen circumscription (for heterotypic synonyms)
         or as TaxonName basionym relationships (for homotypic synonyms) 2) a concept relationship
         where some part of (or all of) the target concept is included in the current
         circumscription. This is more precisely expressed using the set relationships such as 'is
         congruent to'. The HasSynonym term is principally intended for handling legacy
         data.

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#HasVernacular>
base_definition:
The target concept is used as a vernacular concept, at least in part, for
         the current concept. This kind of relationship should not be used to express any form of
         set relationship (e.g. overlaps, is congruent with, includes). Consider using vernacular
         type relationships along with set type relationships to avoid any
         ambiguity.

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#Includes>
base_definition: Set Relationship: Concept 2 is a subset of Concept 1

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#IsAmbiregnalOf>
base_definition:
The two concepts are considered to represent the same taxon (i.e. they are
         congruent) but their names governed by different nomenclatural codes.
com_tcsEquivalence:
/RelationshipType/is ambiregnal of (The definition is somewhat different
         as TaxonConcepts are permitted to have multiple names in the RDF version of
         TCS)

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#IsAnamorphOf>
base_definition:
Concept 1 is the asexual or mitotic reproductive stage in a pleomorphic life
         cycle in which Concept 2 is the teleomorph or meiotic reproductive stage
         .

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#IsChildTaxonOf>
base_definition:
Hierarchical Relationship: Concept 1 is a member of lower taxonomic rank of
         Concept 2

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#IsCongruentTo>
base_definition:
Set Relationship: The extent of Concept 1 is (essentially) identical to
         Concept 2

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#IsFemaleParentOf>
base_definition: Hybrid Relationship: Concept 1 is genetic mother of Concept 2

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#IsFirstParentOf>
base_definition:
Hybrid Relationship: Concept 1 is genetic parent (1) of Concept
         2

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#IsHybridChildOf>
base_definition:
Hybrid Relationship: Concept 2 is a genetic parent of Concept
         1

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#IsHybridParentOf>
base_definition:
Hybrid Relationship: Concept 1 is genetic parent of Concept
         2

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#IsIncludedIn>
base_definition: Set Relationship: Concept 1 is a subset of Concept 2

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#IsMaleParentOf>
base_definition:
Hybrid Relationship: Concept 1 is genetic father of Concept
         2

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#IsNotCongruentTo>
base_definition:
Set Relationship: The extent of Concept 1 is not identical to Concept
         2

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#IsNotIncludedIn>
base_definition: Set Relationship: Concept 1 is not a subset of Concept 2

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#IsParentTaxonOf>
base_definition:
Hierarchical Relationship: Taxon Concept 1 includes Concept 2 as a
         lower-ranked member.

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#IsSecondParentOf>
base_definition:
Hybrid Relationship: Concept 1 is genetic parent (2) of Concept
         2.

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#IsSynonymFor>
base_definition:
The current concept is considered a synonym of the target concept. This is
         an ambiguous relationship. It can mean: 1) a nomenclatural relationship where all that is
         implied is that the type of the current concept is included in the target circumscription.
         This is more precisely expressed as a specimen circumscription (for heterotypic synonyms)
         or as TaxonName basionym relationships (for homotypic synonyms) 2) a concept relationship
         where some part of (or all of) the current concept is included in the target
         circumscription. This is more precisely expressed using the set relationships such as 'is
         congruent to'. The IsSynonymFor term is principally intended for handling legacy
         data.

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#IsTeleomorphOf>
base_definition:
Concept 1 is the teleomorph or meiotic reproductive stage in a pleomorphic
         life cycle in which Concept 2 is the asexual or mitotic reproductive
         stage.

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#IsVernacularFor>
base_definition:
The current concept is used as a vernacular concept, at least in part, for
         the target concept. This kind of relationship should not be used to express any form of set
         relationship (e.g. overlaps, is congruent with, includes). Consider using vernacular type
         relationships along with set type relationships to avoid any ambiguity.

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#nameString>
rdfs_comment:
A string representation of the TaxonName for this concept. Equivalent to TCS
         /DataSet/TaxonConcepts/TaxonConcept/Name/TaxonName/Simple

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#Overlaps>
base_definition:
Set Relationship: Concepts 1 and 2 share members/children in
         common

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#primary>
rdfs_comment:
If primary='true' the concept is the first level response to a query. If 'false'
         the concept may be a secondary concept linked directly or indirectly to the definition of a
         primary concept.

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#rank>
rdfs_comment:
*Deprecated* The taxonomic rank of this concept. This is a link to an instance
         of TaxonomicRank. Compare with the rankString property. Equivalent to TCS
         /DataSet/TaxonConcepts/TaxonConcept/Rank. After discussions between a number of parties
         this property is considered to be deprecated. The rank of a TaxonConcept should be
         indicated by including a TaxonName of the appropriate rank in the hasName property even if
         the name object is empty apart from the rank.

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#rankString>
rdfs_comment:
*Deprecated* The taxonomic rank of this concept as a string. A string
         representation of the rank of this concept. It is highly recommended that the rank property
         be used along with this one unless the correct rank is not available in the rank
         vocabulary. No direct equivalent in TCS but is string version of
         /DataSet/TaxonConcepts/TaxonConcept/Rank. Requested by data suppliers. After discussions
         between a number of parties this property is considered to be deprecated. The rank of a
         TaxonConcept should be indicated by including a TaxonName of the appropriate rank in the
         hasName property even if the name object is empty apart from the rank.

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#Relationship>
rdfs_comment: A typed link to with another taxon.

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#relationshipCategory>
rdfs_comment: The kind of relationship this is.

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#TaxonRelationshipTerm>
rdfs_comment:
The class for constructing a controlled vocabulary for TaxonConcept to
         TaxonConcept relationship categories.

subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/ontology/voc/TaxonConcept#toTaxon>
rdfs_comment: The target taxon in this relationship.
